Found an article in El Paso Herald written by N. M. Walker (The Library of Congress, Cronicling America), issue April 28, 1911; entitled &quot;COMISSIONS BESTOWED BY MADERO ON RANKING OFFICERS OF HIS ARMY&quot;.  In third collumn , subtitle Comissions Bestowed: &quot;....taking a rosetted streamer of the tricolor ribbon, he called Pascual Orozco from his command......  He was no longer Col. Orozco, but held the comission of a brigadier general......&quot;
&quot;Garibaldi had his comission as colonel...  José de la Luz Blanco received his comission as colonel.  Pancho Villa clanked up in his spurs and silver trimmings to be made a colonel.&quot; 
Although Norman Walker does not mention a date, it's quite a deal of possibility this picture can be linked to the event here described, on days close before the publication of the article.
Then the man with the crossed cananas on the chest, to the right of Abraham González, might be José de la Luz Blanco, shaved for the ocassion.
Dr. Roberto Duarte
Plastic Surgeon
